In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims October 2011 as National Breast Cancer Awareness Month. He highlights the importance of raising awareness and supporting those affected by breast cancer. The article mentions that while progress has been made in prevention, early detection, and treatment, many women, including African-American women, continue to be diagnosed with breast cancer. The President emphasizes the need for understanding the risks and precautions associated with breast cancer, such as maintaining a healthy lifestyle and getting regular check-ups. He also mentions the Affordable Care Act, which provides preventive services, including mammograms, with no out-of-pocket costs. The President calls for unity in honoring those lost to breast cancer and supporting efforts to treat and cure the disease. He encourages citizens, organizations, and government agencies to participate in activities that increase awareness and prevention of breast cancer.